    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Largest class of the phylum Mollusca, consisting of about 65,000 species living in the ocean, fresh water, and on land. The name means "belly-footed," referring to the broad tapered foot on which these animals glide. Includes snails, which have a shell into which the animal can withdraw, and slugs, which differ from snails in having shells that are reduced to an internal fragment or completely lost.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>為軟體動物門中的大綱，包含約六萬五千種棲息於海洋、淡水以及陸地的生物。Gastropoda的意思是「腹足」，指其寬大且朝尾端漸細，可用以滑行的肉足。蝸牛為此綱的成員之一，具有外殼，而身體能縮回殼中。蛞蝓亦屬腹足類，與蝸牛不同之處在於牠們的殼已簡化，僅剩一部分的內殼，甚至已完全消失。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
